{"key":"post-9980856","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9980856</id>\n<content>Yes, that's bacteria.&amp;nbsp; Here's your mistakes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;NEVER allow the dishes to remain open for 2 minutes, even in front of a flow hood.&amp;nbsp; While your hood may stop 99.99% of the contaminants, one exhale from you can have billions of bacteria.&amp;nbsp; If your hood filters 99.99% of them, you still dump a few thousand bacteria into your dishes.&amp;nbsp; Follow the five second rule.&amp;nbsp; Never have a dish open for more than five seconds, so this means planning ahead when making inoculations and/or transfers.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Condensation is normal for the first few days after pouring dishes.&amp;nbsp; The agar is warm, and the outside room air is relatively cool.&amp;nbsp; This causes condensation as a fact of science.&amp;nbsp; Leave the dishes in a vertical stack with the sleeve over them, and they'll re-absorb that moisture back into the agar within two to three days.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Don't use syringes to inoculate agar.&amp;nbsp; Syringes are made by pouring water on a print, and no print is sterile.&amp;nbsp; While BRF isn't a great media for bacteria, agar is.&amp;nbsp; Inoculate petri dishes with a flame sterilized inoculating loop directly from a print, and use the minimum amount of spores possible.&amp;nbsp; When the mycelium begins to grow, immediately transfer what you see from the leading edges to new dishes.&amp;nbsp; This way, you can get out ahead of any contaminants that may have been on your print.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Always work in the very center of the flowhood, right up against it.&amp;nbsp; I never open a jar or petri dish unless it's within one inch of the face of the flowhood.&amp;nbsp; Wear gloves, and wash them with 70% alcohol often.&amp;nbsp; Wear a surgical, NOT dust mask, and even then, hold your breath while the dishes or jars are open.&amp;nbsp; In addition, work in a small room with the door and windows closed, and let the flowhood run for at least an hour before beginning work to clean up the ambient air.&amp;nbsp; Two hours is even better.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>9980447</prev>\n<first>9967593</first>\n<last>9980856</last>\n<when>1237217088</when>\n<utime>03/16/09 06:24 PM</utime>\n</post>"}